How does the lwc:spread directive work in LWC? What are its key limitations?
Companies that asked this: Salesforce, Adobe, HubSpot, Microsoft

Answer:
The lwc:spread directive passes multiple properties to a child component using a single object with key-value pairs.

Basic Usage:

// Parent Component
export default class Parent extends LightningElement {
    childProps = { 
        name: "James Smith", 
        country: "USA",
        isActive: true 
    };
}
<!-- Parent Template -->
<template>
    <c-child lwc:spread={childProps}></c-child>
</template>
// Child Component
export default class Child extends LightningElement {
    @api name;
    @api country;
    @api isActive;
}


Key Limitations:

Always applied last - overrides explicit properties

Only one lwc:spread per element

Object keys must match child's @api properties

<!-- Property override example -->
<template>
    <c-child name="Will be overridden" lwc:spread={childProps}></c-child>
    <!-- Result: name = "James Smith" from spread object -->
</template>


Interview Tips:

Explain it simplifies passing multiple properties at once

Emphasize the override behavior and one-spread limitation

Show understanding of key-value pair matching with @api properties
